title.narrative: CHILD HEALTH AND IMMUNIZATION SERVICES

description.narrative: Integrated Management of Childhood illness and Immunization services for Children, adolescent and pregnant women, especially in most vulnerable governorates and in humanitarian situations, are of high quality, sustainable and equitable., which contributes to Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care (Covid), Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2024, all newborns, children, adolescents and women in Iraq access and equitably use affordable, high-impact health and nutrition services, especially the most vulnerable in humanitarian situations.

description.narrative: Despite the challenges of the COVID-19 pandemic and vaccination rollout,UNICEF worked closely with the Ministry of Health to enhance the quality and coverage of routine immunization services, thus ensuring vaccine availability and proper vaccine management, maintaining coverage of measles and diphtheria, tetanus and pertussis third-dose(DTP3) vaccines at; 80 per cent and installing qualified cold chain equipment. With UNICEF support, the Ministry of Health has deployed COVID-19 vaccines, reaching almost 30 per cent of eligible recipients with one dose, and 20 per cent with two doses, in 2021. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:16/01/2022
